<h2><span id="Overview">Overview</span></h2>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/c/ca/Chum_box_example_cnn.png" align="right"/>
<p>'Chumboxes' became very common during the 2010s &ndash; they are often presented to the reader as additional reading intended, and use headings such as <em>"around the web"</em> and <em>"you might like"</em>. The use of chumboxes became common on many mainstream websites, inlcuding those of <a title="CNN" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CNN">CNN</a>, <a title="Fox News" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fox_News">Fox News</a>, <a title="MSNBC" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MSNBC">MSNBC</a>, <a title="USA Today" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USA_Today">USA Today</a>, and others.<sup>[1]</sup></p>
<p>Providers of this content included [1]</sup> Casey Newton (<a title="The Verge" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Verge">The Verge</a>) concluded that the ad format was likely to be short lived, similar to schemes such as <a title="Groupon" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Groupon">Groupon</a>; though clickthrough on such ads was in the single digit percentage region (compared to 0.1% for <a title="Banner ad" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banner_ad">banner ads</a>), this figure was comparable to that early experienced by banner ads &ndash; he expected that as with banner ads, users would eventually come to learn of the low utility of such links, and eventually avoid them.<sup>[1]</sup></p>
<p>By the late mid 2010s</span><sup>[<em><span title="This passage needs to be better explained. (August 2018)">clarify</span></em>]</sup> some internet websites were re-thinking the use of "chumboxes" due to the negative impact such low quality links and content had on their brand, despite the additional income from such links.<sup>[2]</sup> An analysis of images used in advertising of the kind found that 26% used sexually suggestive or "interruptive" images; often the ads had no relation to the article content, and on occasions were innapropiate or offensive, such as one entitled <em>"Meet the Women Making Rape Jokes That Are Actually Funny"</em> place under an article about teenage rape.<sup>[2]</sup></p>
<p>A report by <em>changeadvertising.org</em> that analysed 50 high rank news sites, found over 80% were using such ads, the majority from Taboola or Outbrain &ndash; many were found to be confusing or misleading in their purpose.<sup>[3]</a></sup></p>
<p>An analysis of images and headlines used in such adverts found a number of basic archetypes used &ndash; these included&nbsp;: a sexy image in association with location based adverisment; reverse aging (skin) treatment based, or 'miracle cure'; body shock images (eg triggering <a title="Trypophobia" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trypophobia">Trypophobia</a> etc); celebrity gossip based; tatoo based images, including those simulating body horror/orifices; images of pills; and weight loss.<sup>[4]</sup><sup>[5]</sup></p>


